Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @sweet potato{1}(chopped into 1cm chunks, no need to peel) into 1cm chunks. Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

In an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g}, sweet potato chunks, lentils, @coconut milk{180%ml}, @curry powder mix{1%sachet}, @korma curry paste{50%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @honey{1%tbsp} and @water{100%ml} for the dal (see pantry for both amounts).

Mix to combine, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw meat. Cook so there's no pink in the middle.

Pop a #lid{} on the pan (or cover with some #foil{}) and transfer the dal to the middle shelf of your oven to cook, until the sweet potato is softened and the dal has thickened slightly, ~{30-35%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Just before the dal is ready, cut the @plain naans{2} in half widthways, then put in your #toaster{} until golden.

If you're using the oven, put the naans onto a #baking tray{}. Sprinkle with a little water and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When the dal is ready, remove from the oven.

Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the dal a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot and stir in the @butter{20%g} (see pantry for amount) until melted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Squeeze the juice from half of the lime wedges into the dal.

Taste and season with salt, pepper or more lime juice if needed.

Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share the dal between your #bowls{} along with the naan alongside for dipping.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over. Enjoy!